'''German submarine ''U-640''''' was a [[German Type VIIC submarine|Type VIIC]] [[U-boat]] built for [[Nazi Germany]]'s ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' for service during [[World War II]].
She was laid down on 30 October 1941 by [[Blohm & Voss]], [[Hamburg]] as yard number 616, launched on 23 July 1942 and commissioned on 17 September 1942 under ''[[Oberleutnant zur See]]'' Karl-Heinz Nagel.

==Service History==
The boat's career began with training at [[5th U-boat Flotilla]] on 17 September 1942, followed by active service on 1 May 1943 as part of the [[6th U-boat Flotilla|6th Flotilla]].

In 1 patrol she sank no ships.

===Wolfpacks===
''U-640'' took part in one [[Wolfpack (naval tactic)|wolfpack]], namely
* Iller (12<U+2013>14 May 1943)

===Fate===
There are discrepancies between the fate of ''U-640'' and {{GS|U-657||2}}, which was sunk in the same vicinity around the same time. Paul Kemp<U+2019>s book<ref>{{cite book|last=Kemp|first=Paul|title=U-Boats Destroyed <U+2013> German Submarine Losses in the World Wars|publisher=Arms and Armour Press|pages=117, 118|year=1997|isbn=1-85409-321-5}}</ref> attributes the sinking of British freighter ''Aymeric'' to ''U-640'', and then subsequently sunk by {{HMS|Swale|K217|6}} on the 17 May 1943, whereas UBoat.net attributes this success and fate to ''U-657''.

Uboat.net states that ''U-640'' was sunk on 14 May 1943 in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] in position {{coord|60|32|N|31|05|W}}, by depth charges from a US [[Consolidated PBY Catalina|Catalina]] of VP-84 Squadron. All hands were lost.

